"nl":{"1375–1465":"1375–1465","1390–Female":"1390–Overleden","1398–Male":"1398–Overleden","1355–1433":"1355–1433","1355–1445":"1355–1445","1445":"1445","1433":"1433","1455":"1455","1465":"1465","1355":"1355","1398":"1398","1375":"1375","1382":"1382","1390":"1390","Much Dewchurch, Herefordshire, England":"Much Dewchurch, Herefordshire, England","Kent, England":"Kent, England","Vowchurch, Herefordshire, England":"Vowchurch, Herefordshire, England"},"en":{"1375–1465":"1375–1465","1390–Female":"1390–Deceased","1398–Male":"1398–Deceased","1355–1433":"1355–1433","1355–1445":"1355–1445","1445":"1445","1433":"1433","1455":"1455","1465":"1465","1355":"1355","1398":"1398","1375":"1375","1382":"1382","1390":"1390","Much Dewchurch, Herefordshire, England":"Much Dewchurch, Herefordshire, England","Kent, England":"Kent, England","Vowchurch, Herefordshire, England":"Vowchurch, Herefordshire, England","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Pye","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English (north-West Midlands, Lancashire, Yorkshire, and Norfolk): nickname from Middle English (Old French) <i>pie</i> ‘magpie’, which could be given to someone who wore black and white clothing, had grey-streaked dark hair, or had a loud, chattering voice and impertinent behaviour, or was cunning or sly. The uncomplimentary senses derive from the bird's behavior and are recorded uses of the word in Middle English and early Modern English.","English: occasionally perhaps a topographic or habitational name referring to a house or inn named <i>Pie</i> ‘magpie’. There were two London taverns so named, but whether these gave rise to a hereditary surname is not known. Surnames derived from house and inn signs are rare in English.","English (of Norman origin): nickname from Anglo-Norman French and Middle English <i>pie</i> ‘merciful, compassionate, kind’, a variant of Old French, Anglo-Norman French <i>piu</i>, <i>peu</i>; see   Pew   (2)."],"variants":[{"name":"Pew","meanings":["Welsh: variant of   Pugh  .","English: nickname from Anglo-Norman French <i>pi(u)</i>, <i>piw</i>, <i>peu</i> ‘holy, pious’, also ‘merciful, kind, compassionate’."]},{"name":"Pyatt","meanings":["English (mainly Staffordshire): nickname either from Middle English <i>piot</i> ‘magpie’ (Old French <i>pïot</i>, a diminutive of Old French <i>pie</i>), commonly used to denote a chattering woman, or alternatively from an unrecorded Middle English <i>pyard</i>, an uncomplimentary term derived from the same Old French word + <i>-(h)ard</i>. Compare   Pye  .","Variant of   Piatt  , a surname of French and Walloon origin.","History: This surname (see 2 above) is listed along with the variant <i>Piatt</i> in the (US) National Huguenot Society's register of qualified Huguenot ancestors."]},{"name":"Pie","meanings":["English: variant of   Pye  , in part a cognate of 2 below.","French: nickname from Old French <i>pie</i> ‘magpie’, perhaps given to a talkative person or someone who had a loud, chattering voice.","French (<b>Pié</b>): variant of   Piet   ‘foot’. Compare   Pease   and   Pee  ."]}]},{"name":"Thomas","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["New Testament name, borne by one of Christ's twelve apostles, referred to as ‘Thomas, called Didymus’ (John 11:16; 20:24). <i>Didymos</i> is the Greek word for ‘twin’, and the name is the Greek form of an Aramaic byname meaning ‘twin’. The given name has always been popular throughout Christendom, in part because St Thomas's doubts have made him seem a very human character."],"variants":[]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705195,"age":7,"year":"1382","julianDay":2225826,"title":"Wycliffe's Bible","description":"John Wycliffe, English theologian and professor at the University of Oxford, completed a translation of the Bible from the Latin Vulgate into Middle English. This translation is known as Wycliffe's Bible and was completed around 1382.","url":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Wycliffe%27s_Bible","urlTitle":"Wikipedia - Wycliffe's Bible","jurisdictionLevel":1},{"id":1705197,"age":80,"year":"1455","julianDay":2252488,"title":"Wars of the Roses","description":"Wars of the Roses was a series of English civil wars for control of the throne of England between the royal families House of Lancaster and the House of York. The name of the war was derived as the red rose was the symbol of the Lancastrians and the white rose was the symbol of the Yorks.","url":"https://www.history.com/topics/british-history/wars-of-the-roses","urlTitle":"History - Wars of the Roses","jurisdictionLevel":1}],"lifeSummary":"When Thomas Pye was born in 1375, in Kent, England, his father, Walter Pye I, was 20 and his mother, Elizabeth De La Bere, was 21. He had at least 1 son with Jane de Bromwich. He died in 1465, in his hometown, at the age of 90."},"et":{"1375–1465":"1375–1465","1390–Female":"1390–Surnud","1398–Male":"1398–Surnud","1355–1433":"1355–1433","1355–1445":"1355–1445","1445":"1445","1433":"1433","1455":"1455","1465":"1465","1355":"1355","1398":"1398","1375":"1375","1382":"1382","1390":"1390","Much Dewchurch, Herefordshire, England":"Much Dewchurch, Herefordshire, England","Kent, England":"Kent, England","Vowchurch, Herefordshire, England":"Vowchurch, Herefordshire, England"},"fi":{"1375–1465":"1375–1465","1390–Female":"1390–Kuollut","1398–Male":"1398–Kuollut","1355–1433":"1355–1433","1355–1445":"1355–1445","1445":"1445","1433":"1433","1455":"1455","1465":"1465","1355":"1355","1398":"1398","1375":"1375","1382":"1382","1390":"1390","Much Dewchurch, Herefordshire, England":"Much Dewchurch, Herefordshire, England","Kent, England":"Kent, England","Vowchurch, Herefordshire, England":"Vowchurch, Herefordshire, England"},"fr":{"1375–1465":"1375–1465","1390–Female":"1390–Décédée","1398–Male":"1398–Décédé","1355–1433":"1355–1433","1355–1445":"1355–1445","1445":"1445","1433":"1433","1455":"1455","1465":"1465","1355":"1355"